The concept map visualizes the sequential workflow of digital image formation, tracing how a real-world scene is transformed into a discrete digital representation.

The pipeline initiates when ambient illumination reflects off a scene and is directed through an optics and lens system onto a CMOS or CCD sensor array.

Stage 1 (Sensing & Capture) leverages the photoelectric effect and a Color Filter Array (CFA/Bayer) to perform initial light and color detection.

This sensing stage fundamentally establishes the baseline for dynamic range and color reproduction, heavily guided by literature on sensor noise models.

Stage 2 (Sampling) governs the continuous-to-discrete transition, mapping the continuous optical projection onto a fixed pixel sampling grid.

Adherence to the Nyquist-Shannon sampling theorem preserves detail resolution, whereas theorem violations yield destructive aliasing and moiré artifacts.

Stage 3 (Quantization) represents the final analog-to-digital converter (ADC) phase, translating electrical voltages into discrete digital bit depths.

The map shows a clear cause-and-effect relationship where higher bit depths secure smooth tonal gradients, while lower bit depths cause contouring and banding.

The workflow culminates in the rightmost columns, balancing desirable image quality parameters (resolution, color accuracy) against inherent artifacts and limitations.

Ultimately, the diagram acts as a structural reference connecting physical properties, mathematical sampling criteria, and bit allocations to explain final image fidelity.
